node.text:
Let’s take a brief look at the fuel system and the wing tanks of the A320, and how well it’s engineered.

There is one fuel tank in each wing (divided into an inner and outer cell) and one in the center wing box. The total usable fuel capacity is 24167 l (6384 USgal). The total unusable fuel capacity is 82.1 l (21.7 USgal)

The aircraft also has provision for three Additional Center Tanks (ACTs). One ACT can be installed in the forward cargo compartment and two in the aft cargo compartment. The aircraft can operate with zero, one, two or three ACTs.

The main fuel-pump system moves the fuel from the fuel tanks to the engines. The system has two main fuel-pumps (main pumps) in each wing and two main pumps in the center tank. The wing tank pumps operate continuously at the same time. If a wing tank pump has a failure (or is set to OFF) the other pump automatically supplies fuel. The center tank pumps are set to on or off (by the Fuel Level Sensing Control Units (FLSCUs)

There is so much more to this system then the eye can see, everything is hidden within the tanks or the equipment bays. System that cool the oil are also implemented into the design. As well as venting for proper pressure balance from outside to inside. Not to mention the cross feed system to balance the tanks that feed the engines.

Quantity indicators to tank ignition prevention systems. It’s amazing how much goes into just one system that makes aircraft fly as well as safe to fly.

CFM56 N1,N2 & EGT BASICS.
••The speed of the LP rotor is indicated on ECAM as N1.
••The Low Pressure (LP) rotor has the forward fan, the booster compressor and the LP shaft, all driven by the LP turbine
••The speed of the HP rotor is indicated on the ECAM as N2.
••Hp compressor is also source of bleed air .
••Combustion chamber has 20 fuel nozzles and 2 igniter plugs .
••Fuel pumps, oil pumps , hydraulic pumps, integrated drive generator and fadec alternator are all driven by gearbox.
••The primary parameters, N1, N2, Exhaust Gas Temperature EGT and fuel flow are directly sent by the ECU(Engine control unit) to the ECAM.
••The engine EGT is sensed and averaged by 9 thermocouple probes located in the T49.5 . The actual engine EGT is displayed in the ECAM EWD .
